data.title: GrantsScope - Grantee Discovery Using LLMs
data.description:
GrantsScope is pioneering the intersection of data science and AI to empower donors in the web3 public goods funding (PGF). 

> Our mission? To revolutionize how donors identify and support grantees during PGF rounds.

GrantsScope harnesses the power of data analytics, machine learning, and advanced Large Language Models (LLMs) to enhance project visibility and democratize access to funding. Our experiments are designed to assist donors during quadratic funding rounds on Gitcoin Grants by
- Providing personalized recommendations, helping donors easily navigate the complexity of PGF rounds.
- Offering self-discovery tools that empower donors to explore and connect with projects that resonate with their values.
- Reducing information asymmetry, ensuring donors comprehensively understand the PGF landscape.
data.problem:
### The Challenge: 
In large PGF rounds, where hundreds of grantees vie for attention, the brightest spotlight often falls on those with the strongest marketing. This imbalance creates a cycle where deserving projects may go unnoticed, leading to an uneven distribution of resources and opportunities.

> Information silos create cultural silos!

### The Result: 
This disparity not only places additional burdens on grantees to amplify their visibility but also diverts their focus from creating meaningful impact. As a result, the true potential of PGF is left untapped, and innovation in public goods is stifled.
data.solution:
### Our Solution: GrantsScope
We believe in leveling the playing field. GrantsScope harnesses the power of data analytics, machine learning, and advanced Large Language Models (LLMs) to enhance project visibility and democratize access to funding. Our experiments are designed to assist donors during quadratic funding rounds on Gitcoin Grants by
- Providing personalized recommendations, helping donors easily navigate the complexity of PGF rounds.
- Offering self-discovery tools that empower donors to explore and connect with projects that resonate with their values.
- Reducing information asymmetry, ensuring donors comprehensively understand the PGF landscape.

### Our Impact: 
Here is the list of apps deployed as part of the project implementation:
- August 2024: The GG21 version will combine previously experimented features using LLMs and clustering algorithms to offer one-click grantee recommendations to donors. Visit the app at [https://grantsscope.streamlit.app/](https://grantsscope.streamlit.app/) on or after August 8th.

- April 2024: One-click personalized [Personalized Grantee Recommendations](https://gitcoin-cr3.streamlit.app/) for Citizens Round #3 to re-discover the grantees you’ve supported in the past, explore grantees backed by the community who also champion your favorite projects, and uncover similar but previously unknown grantees

- March 2024: [Clustering-based Discovery tool](https://gp-octant.streamlit.app/) for GreenPill Network x Octant Community Round to guide your exploration of projects by picking a project that sparks your curiosity, discovering similar and distinct projects.

- January 2024: PoCs for [Grantee Recommendations Engine](https://gov.gitcoin.co/t/concepts-pocs-and-early-results-for-personalized-grantee-recommendations/17469) by tapping into historical donation data and for driving interactive visualization to discover similar projects based on clustering.

- December 2023: [Code-created NFT](https://zora.co/collect/oeth:0x4e17da9659cca38ebfd98446d2b404bf94fe9997/1) art to illustrate power of PGF. The art uses a logarithmic scale for brightness to highlight even lesser-known projects, symbolizing their potential to become significant over time.

- December 2023: [2023 Wrapped](https://2023-wrapped-gitcoin.streamlit.app/) with Personalized Grantee Recommendations for Gitcoin Donors. Read full description [here](https://x.com/RohitMalekar/status/1742196496152642030?s=20).

- November 2023:  [Conversational App](https://all-about-gg19.streamlit.app/) for 500+ projects in GG19 – Program Rounds and Climate Solutions Rounds. Examples [here](https://x.com/RohitMalekar/status/1726662662803820789?s=20), [here](https://x.com/RohitMalekar/status/1727055572686782631?s=20), and [here](https://x.com/RohitMalekar/status/1727420457379676430?s=20)!

- October 2023: [Conversational App](https://all-about-gg19.streamlit.app/) for Gitcoin Citizens Round #2,  to explore queries such as who is working on [innovative technical ideas](https://x.com/RohitMalekar/status/1712731683269865628?s=20) or who is [pushing the needle on governance](https://x.com/RohitMalekar/status/1713911298759573965?s=20) or understand a [particular project’s objective](https://x.com/RohitMalekar/status/1712731688781091135?s=20)!

- August 2023: [A ChatGPT-like experience](https://gg18-llm.streamlit.app/) (with conversational memory) to explore 80+ grantees in the Climate Round of GG18, with new feature for capturing user feedback. The app can be used to [write a Twitter thread](https://x.com/RohitMalekar/status/1694430171112026232?s=20) for your project, interact in [language of your choice](https://x.com/RohitMalekar/status/1694430173800677403?s=20), [seek clarification](https://x.com/RohitMalekar/status/1694430177974001789?s=20) for a grantee’s work, and explore [projects by topics](https://x.com/RohitMalekar/status/1694430180834464034?s=20) of your interest.

- June 2023: Focused on the grantees in the inaugural Gitcoin Citizens Round, you can use the [app](https://gitcoin-citizens-round.streamlit.app/) to inquire about the [round](https://x.com/RohitMalekar/status/1671609676063027204?s=20), a [grantee’s impact](https://x.com/zer8_future/status/1671645653951459328?s=20), or search for [projects on a topic ](https://publish-01.obsidian.md/access/b3b1a5dbf3cf3e32fc0222ee239ca0a9/x_Attachments/Screenshot%202023-09-26%20at%203.44.04%20PM%201.png)you care about.


Visit https://grantsscope.xyz/ to access the complete list of apps, source code, and sample results.

Join a growing community of over 500 unique users, as verified by StreamLit analytics, in exploring innovative applications that leverage conversational experiences using LLMs (Large Language Models) and clustering techniques.

### Examples

**One-click personalized grantee recommendations based on donation history**

![](https://grantsscope.files.wordpress.com/2024/04/screenshot-2024-04-18-at-9.47.05-pm.png)

**Grantee discovery using clustering techniques**
![](https://grantsscope.files.wordpress.com/2024/03/zoom-in.gif)

**Rediscovering grantees supported in the past**
![](https://grantsscope.files.wordpress.com/2024/03/ezgif-7-c799965c44.gif)

**LLM-assisted grantee discovery through conversational experience**
![](https://grantsscope.files.wordpress.com/2024/03/qmqk1by9qpp8aew61x2qjidfcxbzp5ea3qnr7iqkfz5sky.jpeg)

### What's next?
As the next milestone, GrantsScope will utilize existing onchain data and clustering techniques to offer personalized recommendations to donors in Gitcoin Grants (GG21). Visit the following link 24 hours after the start of GG21 donations to explore the app - [https://grantsscope.streamlit.app/](https://grantsscope.streamlit.app/)
data.missionSummary:
### The Moonshot

Decentralized communities at times have the same information silos as centralized orgs, not as a result of access but the difficulty of discovery. Persistent information asymmetry leads to long-term damage in building a sustainable culture.

> Information silos create cultural silos.

The lessons learnt from this project can be used to solve the larger problems in discovering actionable content in decentralized communities, such as contributor onboarding and analysis paralysis in governance.

questions.query: How is the project CollabTech?
questions.explanation:
GrantsScope is designed to assist donors in decision making during quadratic funding rounds by:
- Providing personalized recommendations, helping donors easily navigate the complexity of PGF rounds.
- Offering self-discovery tools that empower donors to explore and connect with projects that resonate with their values.
- Reducing information asymmetry, ensuring donors comprehensively understand the PGF landscape.

questions.query: Who's the targeted user group and what's the need/problem being addressed?
questions.explanation:
The Challenge:
In large QF rounds, where hundreds of grantees vie for attention, the brightest spotlight often falls on those with the strongest marketing. This imbalance creates a cycle where deserving projects may go unnoticed, leading to an uneven distribution of resources and opportunities.

Information silos create cultural silos!

The Result:
This disparity not only places additional burdens on grantees to amplify their visibility but also diverts their focus from creating meaningful impact. As a result, the true potential of QF is left untapped, and innovation in public goods is stifled.

questions.query: How do you ensure value keeps being delivered after the round is over? (How will the project become commercially sustainable or a perennial good? )
questions.explanation: The project uses donor contribution graphs and clustering techniques on project descriptions to drive recommendations today. The goal is to make it a perennial public good by continuously integrating data attributes that matter most for donors in decision-making, such as Farcaster Social Graph, Reputation on Open Rank Protocol, etc.

questions.query: How long will it take after funding is received to deliver value? (share a high level timeline)
questions.explanation:
The project is already live in the form of tooling made available during QF rounds and has been used by 500+ unique users. See https://grantsscope.xyz/ for all deployments.

The funding from this round will be used to expand the recommendation engine's data capabilities, and the updated algorithm will be available for GG22 by the end of the year.

questions.query: Describe your team's expertise in your chosen focus area within Web3 grants. Include relevant experience, publications, or past projects.
questions.explanation:
Related publications in public goods space:
**[Cluster-matching Quadratic Funding](https://www.gitcoin.co/blog/wtf-is-cluster-matching-qf):** Authored overview of plural capital allocation mechanism
- **[Augmented Bonding Curve](https://hackernoon.com/inside-open-collectives-effort-to-become-decentralized-for-global-public-good):** Research on mechanism design for exit to community
- **[DAO Strategy](https://github.com/rohitmalekar/codeless-conduct-feb2022/blob/main/Codeless%20Conduct%20DAO%20Strategy.md):** Hackathon winner by [quadratic vote](https://quadraticvote.radicalxchange.org/event?id=f47b49ca-b279-421c-bc5f-c5118f43750d) at [Codeless Conduct Hackathon](https://gitcoin.co/issue/1kxnetwork/codelessconduct/6/100027751)
- **[The Product Management Grid](https://uxdesign.cc/product-management-grid-a5f392f6e4a5):** Designed framework for outcomes-driven app development
- **[HackerNoon Contributor of the Year (2022)](https://www.noonies.tech/2022/web3/2022-hackernoon-contributor-of-the-year-dao):** Runner-up for writings published in the DAO category

questions.query: How does your project contribute to the growth of the OSS ecosystem? Please provide specific examples of how your application enhances or expands the current ecosystem.
questions.explanation:
GrantsScope contributes to the growth of the Open Source Software (OSS) ecosystem by democratizing access to funding, increasing discoverability of under-the-radar OSS projects, and helping donors make informed, value-aligned decisions at scale. Two most recent examples are as follows:

In August 2024, during Gitcoin Grants 21, GrantsScope delivered one-click grantee recommendations using clustering and LLMs based on a donor’s historical donations.
📌 This helped donors discover lesser-known but thematically aligned OSS projects that they would have otherwise missed.

In November 2024, we deployed a tool that let donors sort OSS projects based on metrics like commit frequency, contributor diversity, and repo activity.
🔍 This empowered donors to support projects based on objective health indicators instead of follower count or hype.

questions.query: What features or use cases does your dApp/App present? How is it differentiated?
questions.explanation:
Our core differentiator lies in using AI, data science, and donor-centric design to address funding discovery and insight gaps. Here are few of the differentiated features:

1. Personalized Grantee Recommendations: Recommends grantees to donors based on their past donation history, similarity to supported projects, and inferred interests.

2. Conversational Exploration of Grantees: Users can ask questions like “Who’s working on decentralized identity?” or “Show me climate-focused OSS projects in this round.”

3. Data-Driven Project Evaluation Metrics: Offers OSS-specific metrics like commit counts, contributors, repo activity, and engagement to help donors make informed decisions.

🧪 Text-to-SQL Prototype (In Progress)
What it does: Lets users ask database-level questions in plain English (e.g., “Which projects have >10 contributors?”) — converted and executed via SQL automatically.

Use case: Enables non-technical ecosystem designers or donors to generate insights without coding.

💥 Differentiator: Democratizes insight generation across the QF stack — from DAO stewards to first-time funders.
